import Mathlib

/-!
  If f : U ‚Üí ‚ÑÇ is holomorphic on a domain U ‚äÇ ‚ÑÇ, then f is analytic.
  In particular, for any z0 ‚àà U there is a Taylor series centered at z0
  which converges on the disk of radius R, where R is the distance to the
  nearest singularity (possibly R = ‚àû), and the sum of the series equals f.

  The statement is given here in a compact form; the proof is omitted (sorry).
-/

open Complex

theorem holomorphic_on_is_analytic {U : Set ‚ÑÇ} (hU : IsOpen U) {f : ‚ÑÇ ‚Üí ‚ÑÇ}
  (hf : IsHolomorphicOn f U) :
  ‚àÄ z0 ‚àà U,
    ‚àÉ R : ‚Ñù, 0 < R ‚àß (‚àÄ z, dist z z0 < R ‚Üí (‚àë' (n : ‚Ñï), (deriv^[n] f) z0 / (n! : ‚ÑÇ) * (z - z0) ^ n) = f z) :=
by
  sorry

/-!
  If f : U ‚Üí ‚ÑÇ is holomorphic on a domain U ‚äÇ ‚ÑÇ, then f is analytic.
  Here we state a standard version: if f is complex-differentiable on an open
  set U, then f is analytic on U. The proof is omitted (sorry).
-/

theorem complex_differentiable_on_implies_analytic_on {U : Set ‚ÑÇ} (hU : IsOpen U)
  {f : ‚ÑÇ ‚Üí ‚ÑÇ} (hf : DifferentiableOn ‚ÑÇ f U) :
  AnalyticOn ‚ÑÇ f U := by
  sorry
